\begin_layout Subsection*
Is there a business case for CSR targeting social good instead of primary
 stakeholder demands?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Barnett (2016) argues that the win-win findings of the CSP-CFP literature
 are not evidence of a business case for CSR but instead confirmation of
 resource dependence theory.
 If CSR motivated by responding to primary stakeholder demands increases
 financial performance, it simply means that firms that undertake actions
 to satisfy the demands of external actors with power over the firm–the
 definition of primary stakeholders–confirm resource dependence theory,
 not demonstrate a business case for CSR.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Building a business case for CSR actions that address the needs of society
 rather than primary stakeholders requires assessing how CSR actions addressing
 social problems and not primary stakeholders demands affects CFP.
 Barnett (2016) steps toward a business case for social good CSR by theorizing
 how CSR affects whether primary stakeholders trust the firm.
 This separates CSR actions from those responding to primary stakeholder
 demands while still allowing for social good CSR to increase CFP through
 the channel of increased commitment and interest from primary stakeholders.
 
