\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
The effect of primary stakeholder CSR on CFP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Answering the first question, corporate financial performance 
\begin_inset Formula $CFP$
\end_inset

 is a function of the firm's CSR reputation 
\begin_inset Formula $CRep$
\end_inset

 and characteristics of the CSR action 
\begin_inset Formula $CChar$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
CFP=f(CRep,CChar)\label{eq:Barnett-2016-model-of-CFP}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Barnett theorizes five propositions about the relationship between CSR character
istics and their effect on the firm's relationship with primary stakeholders:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The more a CSR action benefits the firm, the less it will increase primary
 stakeholder trust,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The less costly a CSR action is for the firm, the less it will increase
 primary stakeholder trust,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The longer a firm waits to implement a CSR action, the less it will increase
 primary stakeholder trust,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The less sustained a firm's CSR action, the less it will increase primary
 stakeholder trust, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The more a firm promotes its CSR action, the less it will increase primary
 stakeholder trust.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting the five propositions for Model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Barnett-2016-model-of-CFP"

\end_inset

's 
\begin_inset Formula $CChar$
\end_inset

 produces the expanded model:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
CFP=f(CRep,CBenefit,CCost,CTiming,CSustain,CPromotion)\label{eq:Expanded-Barnett-model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

