\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Extending Barnett beyond primary stakeholders
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I argue Model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Barnett-2016-model-of-CFP"

\end_inset

 omits a crucial factor in explaining how a firm's CSP affects CFP: characterist
ics of the stakeholders being targeted by CSR action 
\begin_inset Formula $CStake$
\end_inset

.
 I argue the model should be:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
CFP=f(CRep,CChar,CStake)\label{eq:CFP-model-with-endogenizing-stakeholder-characteristics}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:CFP-model-with-endogenizing-stakeholder-characteristics"

\end_inset

's inclusion of stakeholder characteristics builds on prior research suggesting
 CSR targeting different stakeholders matters to financial performance in
 different ways.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Firm relationship with primary stakeholders
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Favor with primary stakeholders 
\begin_inset Formula $PF$
\end_inset

 is a function of power 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and trust 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
PF=f(P,T)\label{eq:stakeholder favor}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Primary stakeholder relationship 
\begin_inset Formula $SR$
\end_inset

 is a function of how the firm deals with stakeholder demands 
\begin_inset Formula $SD$
\end_inset

 and stakeholder reaction 
\begin_inset Formula $SR$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
SR=f(SD,SR)\label{eq:stakeholder-relationship}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

